{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_5","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' literature_review.md\"","aggregated_output":"## Literature Review\n\n### Research Area Overview\nThis project sits at the intersection of universal algebra, equational logic, finite model theory, and automated theorem proving.\n\nThe concrete target is the implication problem over magmas:\n- Given two equations (laws) `E1, E2` in a single binary operation, decide whether `E1 |= E2`.\n- In finite-model variants, decide whether `E1 |=_fin E2`.\n\nThis aligns directly with the Equational Theories Project (ETP), which exhaustively studied implication relations among 4694 low-complexity magma laws.\n\nSubfield and indexing cues:\n- Primary: universal algebra / relation algebras (`math.RA` in the ETP preprint)\n- Supporting: logic in computer science (`cs.LO`), machine learning for ATP (`cs.LG`)\n- Useful MSC-style themes: equational classes/varieties, term rewriting, automated deduction, finite model methods.\n\nSearch keywords used:\n- equational law implication magma\n- equational logic universal algebra\n- finite model finding equational theories\n- Prover9 Mace4 equational theorem proving\n- learned guidance equational theorem prover\n- latent space equational theories\n- abstraction learning theorem proving\n\n### Key Definitions\nDefinition 1 (Magma): A structure `(M, *)` with a set `M` and one binary operation `* : M x M -> M`.\n\nDefinition 2 (Equational law): A universally quantified identity between two terms in variables built from the binary operation.\n\nDefinition 3 (Implication of laws): `E1 |= E2` means every magma satisfying `E1` also satisfies `E2`.\n\nDefinition 4 (Finite implication): `E1 |=_fin E2` means every finite magma satisfying `E1` also satisfies `E2`.\n\nDefinition 5 (Countermodel): A magma `M` such that `M |= E1` but `M !|= E2`, witnessing `E1 !|= E2`.\n\nDefinition 6 (Implication graph): Directed graph on laws, with edge `E -> E'` exactly when implication holds.\n\n### Key Papers\n\n#### Paper 1: The Equational Theories Project: Advancing Collaborative Mathematical Research at Scale\n- Authors: M. Bolan et al.\n- Year: 2025\n- Source: arXiv:2512.07087\n- Main Results:\n  - Determined all 22,028,942 nontrivial implication/non-implication relationships among 4694 basic magma laws.\n  - Formalized proofs/refutations in Lean.\n  - Studied both full implication and finite-implication variants.\n- Proof Techniques:\n  - Explicit finite countermodel search.\n  - Linear and translation-invariant model constructions.\n  - Twisting-semigroup comparisons.\n  - Greedy extension constructions (abstract greedy framework).\n  - Syntactic invariants and rewriting-style arguments.\n  - ATP-assisted proof search with Lean verification.\n- Relevance to Our Research:\n  - Direct benchmark and methodology source for deciding `E1 => E2` over magmas.\n  - Provides a ready structure for model-guided implication prediction and proof/counterexample generation.\n\n#### Paper 2: Learning Equational Theorem Proving\n- Authors: J. Piepenbrock, T. Heskes, M. Janota, J. Urban\n- Year: 2021\n- Source: arXiv:2102.05547\n- Main Results:\n  - Introduces 3SIL (Stratified Shortest Solution Imitation Learning) for equational proving.\n  - Reports competitive standalone theorem-proving performance and improved cooperative performance with Prover9.\n- Proof/Method Techniques:\n  - RL/IL-guided rewriting policy learning.\n  - Tree-structured state encoding.\n  - Hybrid mode: learned lemma suggestions + symbolic prover.\n- Relevance:\n  - Strong precedent for model-guided (\"cheatsheet-like\") guidance to accelerate implication proving.\n\n#### Paper 3: The Latent Space of Equational Theories\n- Authors: L. Berlioz, P.-A. Mellies\n- Year: 2026\n- Source: arXiv:2601.20759\n- Main Results:\n  - Constructs a latent representation of equational theories from behavior on many finite magmas.\n  - Observes oriented reasoning flows in this latent geometry.\n- Techniques:\n  - Statistical embedding of theories, finite-model behavior signatures, graph-based implication analysis.\n- Relevance:\n  - Suggests a data-derived feature space for ranking likely implications before proof search.\n\n#### Paper 4: Twitch: Learning Abstractions for Equational Theorem Proving\n- Authors: G. Axelrod, M. Johansson, N. Smallbone\n- Year: 2026\n- Source: arXiv:2603.06849\n- Main Results:\n  - Learns reusable abstraction patterns from failed/related proofs.\n  - Integrates abstractions into Twee to solve additional UEQ/TPTP problems and speed up search.\n- Techniques:\n  - Abstraction mining from proof traces.\n  - Pattern-guided prioritization in saturation/completion style proving.\n- Relevance:\n  - Directly supports building a compact \"cheatsheet prompt\" of useful term/lemma patterns.\n\n#### Paper 5: Mace4 Reference Manual and Guide\n- Author: W. McCune\n- Year: 2003\n- Source: arXiv:cs/0310055\n- Main Results/Content:\n  - Defines practical finite model search workflow for first-order/equational inputs.\n- Techniques:\n  - Grounding + SAT-assisted search for finite structures.\n- Relevance:\n  - Core toolchain for quickly disproving candidate implications by finite countermodels.\n\n### Known Results (Prerequisite Theorems)\nTheorem A (Birkhoff completeness for equations):\nFor equational logic, semantic consequence over all algebras is equivalent to derivability in equational proof calculus (equation substitution + congruence + transitivity rules).\n- Source: standard universal algebra, cited by ETP.\n- Used for: reducing implication proving to derivation search when complete proof systems are available.\n\nResult B (Duality symmetry of magma laws):\nIf `E1 |= E2`, then dualized laws satisfy `E1* |= E2*` (operation reversal).\n- Source: ETP foundational section.\n- Used for: halving search effort by symmetry transfer.\n\nResult C (Finite countermodel methodology):\nSmall finite magmas, linear constructions, translation-invariant constructions, and greedy constructions provide broad non-implication witnesses.\n- Source: ETP Sections 5 and 8.\n- Used for: negative implication detection (`E1 !|= E2`) before expensive proof search.\n\nResult D (Hybrid ML + symbolic proving):\nLearned guidance can improve symbolic prover effectiveness, especially as lemma/shape proposals.\n- Source: Piepenbrock et al. 2021; Axelrod et al. 2026.\n- Used for: designing model-guided cheatsheet prompts for implication tasks.\n\n### Proof Techniques in the Literature\n- Finite model enumeration/counterexample search: used heavily in ETP and operationalized by Mace4-style workflows.\n- Algebraic model templates (linear, translation-invariant): constructive counterexamples beyond brute force.\n- Structural invariants / semigroup comparisons: synthetic non-implication proofs.\n- Completion and saturation proving (Twee/Prover9 style): standard for positive implication proofs.\n- Learned guidance:\n  - action/rewriting policies (3SIL)\n  - abstraction templates from proof corpora (Twitch)\n  - latent geometry priors over theories (latent-space paper)\n\nPotential applicability to our question:\n- Most promising stack is two-stage: (1) countermodel-first filter; (2) guided proof search with a compact prompt describing known useful rewrites/lemmas/term shapes.\n\n### Related Open Problems\n- ETP reports a tiny set of difficult residual implications at intermediate project stages; one explicitly mentioned unresolved-at-stage pair appears as `E677` vs `E255` for finite implication investigations.\n- More broadly open: principled evaluation of which ATP/ML guidance mechanism works best by implication-type region in the graph.\n- Open engineering problem: converting learned latent/geometric signals into reliable proof-producing guidance with calibrated confidence.\n\n### Gaps and Opportunities\n- Gap 1: Reliable theorem-certifying guidance\n  - ML methods rank actions well but do not by themselves produce trusted proofs.\n  - Opportunity: enforce proof-object generation/checking in Lean/ATP pipeline.\n\n- Gap 2: Unified implication decision pipeline\n  - Literature splits across model-finders, symbolic provers, and learned policies.\n  - Opportunity: combine them into a single controller for `E1 => E2` with fallback logic.\n\n- Gap 3: Prompt/cheatsheet design theory\n  - Evidence exists that guidance helps, but little formal analysis of prompt structure for equational ATP.\n  - Opportunity: treat cheatsheet synthesis as a constrained abstraction-learning problem.\n\n### Recommendations for Proof Strategy\nBased on literature review:\n- Recommended approach:\n  - Use a layered solver:\n    1) fast finite countermodel search (`E1 & not E2`) to reject false implications;\n    2) guided symbolic proof search for surviving pairs;\n    3) proof checking/export in Lean or proof-certificate format.\n\n- Key lemmas to establish in project design:\n  - Soundness of the guidance policy (it only prioritizes steps; does not change logic).\n  - Correctness of model-to-feature extraction for cheatsheet terms.\n  - Symmetry-transfer lemma for dual laws to reduce workload.\n\n- Potential obstacles:\n  - Search-space explosion for positive implications without strong heuristics.\n  - Distribution shift between training implications and hard long-tail implications.\n  - Nontrivial mapping from learned suggestions to accepted prover tactics.\n\n- Computational support:\n  - `Mace4`-style finite model finding for negatives.\n  - `Prover9`/`Twee`-style ATP for positives.\n  - `sympy` and custom scripts for preprocessing/rewrite normalization.\n  - PDF/metadata processing artifacts in `artifacts/` for reproducibility.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
