{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_23","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' planning.md\"","aggregated_output":"## Research Question\nGiven two equations over magmas, can a compact cheatsheet-guided procedure reliably answer whether Equation 1 implies Equation 2 (Stage 1 output: `true`/`false`)?\n\n## Motivation & Novelty Assessment\n\n### Why This Research Matters\nEquational implication over magmas is a core reasoning primitive in universal algebra and automated theorem proving. Fast implication judgments can reduce proof-search cost, improve theorem-prover routing, and make large implication graphs (such as ETP) operational for downstream tools. A robust `true`/`false` stage-1 policy is directly useful for benchmark participation and for triaging harder proof obligations.\n\n### Gap in Existing Work\n`literature_review.md` shows strong components exist independently: finite countermodel search, symbolic proving, and learned guidance. The missing piece is a minimal, reproducible, prompt-oriented workflow that maps directly onto the Stage 1 interface (single-pair implication decision) with explicit failure modes and evidence artifacts.\n\n### Our Novel Contribution\nWe test a hybrid, lightweight pipeline tailored to Stage 1: (1) finite countermodel search for fast falsification, (2) bounded equational closure for positive support, and (3) a cheatsheet decision protocol that converts evidence into a strict boolean answer.\n\n### Experiment Justification\n- Experiment 1: Validate falsification via exhaustive finite magma search (`n<=3`) to verify practical non-implication detection.\n- Experiment 2: Validate bounded derivation closure to capture implication patterns that follow directly from substitution/congruence.\n- Experiment 3: Evaluate combined policy on a curated benchmark with known truth values to assess decision reliability and runtime.\n\n## Background and Motivation\nThe Equational Theories Project established large-scale implication structure among low-complexity magma laws. Stage 1 of the competition asks for boolean implication decisions. A practical research objective is therefore not full theorem-proving completeness, but a reproducible, evidence-guided decision stack that is transparent and easy to improve.\n\n## Hypothesis Decomposition\n- H1: If `E1` does not imply `E2`, small finite countermodels often witness this quickly.\n- H2: If `E1` implies `E2` through short equational reasoning, bounded closure over small term universes can detect it.\n- H3: A policy combining H1 and H2 can provide useful Stage 1 boolean answers with interpretable evidence.\n\nIndependent variables:\n- Maximum magma order in falsification search (`max_order`)\n- Term depth and substitution limits in bounded closure (`max_depth`, `sub_limit`)\n\nDependent variables:\n- Decision accuracy on benchmark\n- Runtime per query\n- Fraction of decisions supported by explicit evidence (countermodel or derivation)\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- Correct decisions on curated benchmark\n- Mean runtime under practical threshold (<1s per pair on benchmark scale used here)\n- 100% reproducibility from scripts\n\n## Proposed Methodology\n\n### Approach\nUse a layered solver:\n1. **Finite-model falsifier**: enumerate all magmas up to a bounded order and return `false` when a countermodel to implication is found.\n2. **Bounded prover**: build equational closure over generated terms and return `true` when `E2` is derivable from `E1`.\n3. **Decision policy**: if falsifier finds witness => `false`; else if bounded prover derives => `true`; else conservative fallback => `true` with explicit uncertainty note (Stage 1 requires boolean output).\n\n### Experimental Steps\n1. Formalize parser/evaluator for magma terms and universal equation checking.\n2. Implement exhaustive finite-model search for counterexamples.\n3. Implement bounded equational closure via substitution + congruence.\n4. Build benchmark harness and runtime/accuracy logging.\n5. Produce summary metrics and visualization.\n\n### Baselines\n- Baseline A: Always `true`.\n- Baseline B: Countermodel-only decision (`false` if witness else `true`).\n- Proposed: Countermodel + bounded derivation.\n\n### Evaluation Metrics\n- Accuracy on curated labeled benchmark\n- Precision/recall for `false` decisions\n- Mean/median runtime\n- Evidence coverage (countermodel or derivation attached)\n\n### Statistical Analysis Plan\nGiven small benchmark size, we use descriptive statistics and Wilson confidence intervals for accuracy. No null-hypothesis test is emphasized due low sample size; effect direction is compared against baselines.\n\n## Expected Outcomes\n- Strong non-implication detection from finite search.\n- Limited but meaningful positive implication detection from bounded closure.\n- Combined policy at least matching countermodel baseline, with richer evidence traces.\n\n## Timeline and Milestones\n1. Resource review and planning (completed first).\n2. Environment verification and dependencies.\n3. Core implementation (`src/`).\n4. Benchmark execution and metrics.\n5. Reporting (`REPORT.md`, `README.md`).\n\n## Potential Challenges\n- Finite search incompleteness relative to all magmas.\n- Bounded closure may miss deeper derivations.\n- Benchmark may not represent full competition distribution.\n\nMitigations:\n- Explicitly label bounded assumptions.\n- Save countermodels/derivation traces.\n- Keep solver modular for stronger provers later.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- End-to-end scripts run in clean `.venv`.\n- Reproducible `results/metrics.json` and figure outputs.\n- Clear cheatsheet protocol yielding strict boolean answers.\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
